<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/25890748-rose-bud"><img alt="" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_100x100-259587f1619f5253426a4fa6fb508831.png" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/25890748-rose-bud">Rose.bud</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">I kind of see what your saying but think that with this series Ms. Rivers wants to get the reader fully immersed into the time and era. So there is a <a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">I kind of see what your saying but think that with this series Ms. Rivers wants to get the reader fully immersed into the time and era. So there is a lot of description, but mostly only at the beginning. If you can press through, (or just skip a few pages ;) of description you will see that it was well worth the press. But if you do skip you'll wind up going back through it like I did, (lol). By the time I finished the book I felt like I was there in that time period with Hadassah and the rest. Hadassah was like part of my family by the time I finished the first one. Ms. Rivers really out did herself with these three. I loved them all. And don't stop with the first one! Trust me you have to read all three. I do believe they are well worth the read.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
